def uniplot(df,col,title,hue =None):
    
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.set_context('talk')
    plt.rcParams["axes.labelsize"] = 20
    plt.rcParams['axes.titlesize'] = 22
    plt.rcParams['axes.titlepad'] = 30
    
    
    temp = pd.Series(data = hue)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    width = len(df[col].unique()) + 7 + 4*len(temp.unique())
    fig.set_size_inches(width , 8)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.title(title)
    ax = sns.countplot(data = cars, x= col, order=cars[col].value_counts().index,hue = hue,palette='bright') 
        
    plt.show()

Conclusion¶

In this blog, we have employed Python and its data visualization libraries to explore a car dataset. By creating visualizations like [barplot,countplot,scatterplot,pairplot], we were able to effectively analyze the Univarient and Bivariate Analysis. Our visualization revealed [Brand,Model,Transmission,Fuel_type,Mileage,Price]. By utilizing Python for data analysis and visualization, we were able to transform raw data into actionable knowledge, highlighting the importance of these techniques in various academic fields.
